A seven-year-old leukemia survivor from California gave an impassioned speech urging his school district to endorse upcoming legislation in support of vaccination.

Rhett Krawitt may not have been big enough to reach the microphone without a chair, but he made his voice heard as he spoke of the illness he conquered. 

'For three-and-a-half years I took chemo to get the bad guys out,' the child said. 'Now I can say gone with cancer.'  

On Thursday he urged elected officials at his Martin County school to support an upcoming bill that would prevent parents from opting out of required vaccines for their children because of personal beliefs.

