The Reed Union School District agreed and voted in support of the upcoming legislation that will be introduced by California Sen. Richard Pan, who is also a pediatrician.

Pan said the bill will work to halt the spread of measles throughout the state, adding 'we want to raise the immunization rate so that we can protect children like Rhett and others'.  

California, which is one of 20 states to have personal belief exemption laws, has especially come under fire recently as the vaccination debate rages on. 

A recent investigation by Wired found that six out of 12 daycares at Silicon Valley tech companies, including Google, have below-average vaccination rates.  

There was a record number of measles cases last year, with 644 infections from 27 states, despite the fact that the disease was largely eradicated in 2000.

